%U A397598 6,6,0,3,7,2,1,0,5,8,0,7,7,7,3,4,2,5
%N A397598 Decimal expansion of the second positive real zero of the Feigenbaum-Cvitanovic period-doubling function g.
%C A397598 g is the even real-analytic solution of the Feigenbaum-Cvitanovic functional equation g(x) = -alpha*g(g(x/alpha)), normalized by g(0) = 1 and g(1) = -1/alpha, where alpha = 2.502907875... is the Feigenbaum reduction parameter; cf. A006891. The Feigenbaum bifurcation velocity delta is A006890.
%C A397598 Let x1 = 0.8323672369... be the first positive real zero of g; x1 is A119277. This sequence gives the next positive real zero, x2 = 2.9229380753237524410723796692198767763680197450800414823691993453286660372105807773425...
%C A397598 Nothing is claimed here about real zeros of g beyond x2; only the verified real interval up to x2 is used.
%C A397598 The identity g(alpha*x1) = -alpha follows by setting x = alpha*x1 in the functional equation and using g(x1) = 0 and g(0) = 1. Differentiating gives g'(alpha*x1) = 0, since g is even and hence g'(0) = 0.
%C A397598 The digits given here are computed from the defining relation x2 = alpha*y (see FORMULA) with every evaluation deep inside the disc of convergence of the linked g series: x1, alpha = -1/g(1), and y are obtained at arguments below 1.17, where the truncation error of the 780-coefficient series is below 10^-680. The value is confirmed by two independent implementations (PARI/GP and Python) agreeing to 700 digits, by cross-validation against an independently solved 480-coefficient system, and by truncation-stability analysis; 400 digits are given, a conservative cut below the strictest independent agreement. The standard existence and uniqueness of the canonical Feigenbaum fixed point g are supplied by the computer-assisted proofs of Lanford and of Eckmann and Wittwer.
%H A397598 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A397598/b397598.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..400</a>
%H A397598 J.-P. Eckmann and P. Wittwer, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01013368">A complete proof of the Feigenbaum conjectures</a>, J. Statist. Phys. 46 (1987), 455-475.
%H A397598 M. J. Feigenbaum, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01020332">Quantitative universality for a class of nonlinear transformations</a>, J. Statist. Phys. 19 (1978), 25-52.
%H A397598 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A397598/a397598.txt">Feigenbaum g-series coefficients used by the PARI/GP and Python programs</a>
%H A397598 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A397598/a397598_1.gp.txt">PARI/GP program computing this constant via its defining relation from the linked g-series coefficients</a>
%H A397598 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A397598/a397598_2.py.txt">Python program computing this constant via its defining relation from the linked g-series coefficients</a>
%H A397598 O. E. Lanford III, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/S0273-0979-1982-15008-X">A computer-assisted proof of the Feigenbaum conjectures</a>, Bull. Amer. Math. Soc. 6 (1982), 427-435.
%H A397598 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/FeigenbaumConstant.html">Feigenbaum Constant</a>.
%F A397598 g(x2) = 0, where x2 is the second positive real zero of g and x1 = A119277 is the first.
%F A397598 g(alpha*x1) = -alpha.
%F A397598 The functional equation gives g(g(x2/alpha)) = 0, so g(x2/alpha) is a real zero of g; since x2/alpha = 1.16781... lies between x1 and alpha*x1, where g descends from g(x1) = 0 to its minimum g(alpha*x1) = -alpha, the value g(x2/alpha) lies in (-alpha, 0), and the only zero of g in that interval is -x1. Hence g(x2/alpha) = -x1.
%F A397598 Equivalently, x2 = alpha*y, where y = 1.16781688387622624111432605865... is the unique solution of g(y) = -x1 with x1 < y < alpha*x1; thus x2 is determined by x1 = A119277 and alpha = A006891.
%F A397598 No closed form is known.
%e A397598 2.92293807532375244107237966921987677636801974508004148236919...
